by Moaz Magdy¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset consists of information regarding 183412 trip from Ford GoBike on Feb, 2019. In this notebook, I'll do some exploratory data analysis for the data on hand.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 trips in this dataset with 16 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip).

There are 5 numeric features in nature (duration_sec, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, and end_station_longitude).
Also, there are 2 datetime features (started_at, and ended_at).
And, there are 9 categorical features (bike_id, start_station_id, end_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_name, member_birth_year, bike_share_for_all_trip, member_gender, and user_type).

member_gender feature has two categories: 'male', 'female' and 'other'.
user_type feature has also two categories: 'Customer', and 'Subscriber'.
bike_share_for_all_trip feature is a boolean feature having two categories: 'yes', and 'no'.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the trip duration. Aiming at that goal, I'll try to answer the following questions:

1. How long does the trip takes on average?,<br/> 
2. Does it depend on user type?, <br/>
3. Does it depend on the time of the day? <br/>
4. How does average trip duration change over the week?, <br/>
5. Do Age and Sex of user affect the duration?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the following features will be the most important in our investigation:

  • 'start_time': will help in determining the day of the week and time of the day for each trip,
  • 'user_type': indicates whether the user is a memeber or a casual customer,
  • 'member_gender': might have a strong relation with the trip duration, and
  • 'member_birth_year': will be used to calculate the age of each user and may have a correlation with trip duration.

The distribution is highly right_skewed with several extreme values. So, we will consider trip durations greater than the maximum whisker (Q3 + 1.5 IQR) as outliers and we will drop them out.

In [23]:
# Calculate Q3
duration_q3 = data.duration_min.quantile(0.75)
# Calculate IQR
duration_IQR = data.duration_min.quantile(0.75) - data.duration_min.quantile(0.25)
# Get the index of outliers
outliers_indx = data.query('duration_min > @duration_q3 + @duration_IQR * 1.5').index
# Drop the outliers
data.drop(index= outliers_indx, inplace= True)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration took a large range of values. It was highly right-skewed so I looked at the data using log transformation. After transformation, the data looked unimodal, with one large peak around 10.

Trips took place mainly at two time over the day, first at 8 am, and second at 5 pm.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

We needed to convert the datatype of some features as follows:

  1. 'start_time' and 'end_time' features are converted from 'object' into 'datatime' to facilitate extracting time related info from this feature,
  2. 'user_type', and 'member_gender' features are converted from 'object' into 'category' to facilitate calculating summary statistics and creating visualizations, and
  3. 'member_birth_year' feature is converted from 'float' into 'int' to facilitate ploting using appropriate plot type.

Also, We created new features from the original features of the dataset to get our variables of interest like:

  1. day_of_week: extracted from 'started_at' datetime feature,
  2. time_of_day: also extracted 'started_at' datetime feature,
  3. member_age: calculated from 'member_birth_year' feature, and
  4. duration_min: calculated from 'duration_sec' feature.

# Function to divide the age into chunks
def age_bin(x):
    if x < 27:
        return 'below 27'
    elif x < 32:
        return 'between 27 and 32'
    elif x < 39:
        return 'between 32 and 39'
    else:
        return 'Above 39'
In [38]:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Surprisingly, the average trip duration didn't change over the week while I expected it to be different for weekends.

Also, it was surprising to me to know that trip duration doesn't depend on member age.

As expected, customers tend to have longer trips than subscribers because they may ride for long trips compared to routine daily commuting for subscribers.

In contrary to what we expected, males and females seem to ride for similar trip durations on average. This may be explained by the large proportion of females who are customers compared to the proportion of males who are customers.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

We observed that most of subscribers are males who may use bikes for their daily commuting. On the other hand, the proportion of subscribers from females is smaller compared to males.

Different of what I have expected, riding times over the day don't depend on the gender. Both males and females seem to have similar riding time pattern.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I'll preform some multivariate explorations to further explore the data on hand.

To start by, I'll check the relationship between the gender, trip duration, and user type.

In [45]:
# Create a boxplot between member_gender, duration_min and user_type

plt.legend(loc = [1,0.8], title= 'User Type');

The above box plot shows that the trip duration for customers is consistently longer than that of subscribers regardless of the gender.

Next, I'll check if the relationship between the trip duration, and day of week depndes on the user type.

In [46]:
# Create a boxplot between day_of_week, duration_min, and user_type.
plt.figure(figsize= (14,6))
sns.boxplot(data= data, x = 'day_of_week', y= 'duration_min', hue= 'user_type', 
            order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday'])
plt.legend(loc = [1,0.8], title= 'User Type');

The above box plot shows that the trip duration for customers is consistently longer than that of subscribers over the week, and specially on weekends. This may be due to the fact that customers are irregular users who ride occationally for entertainment purpose.

Now, I'll check if there are some days over the week when males tend to ride longer than females.
